Fundamentally, it's a different settings view on the existing wifi/vpn/mobile restrictions and the addition of a "restrict new apps". Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

On 4.14 kernels, there is no LEX and YACC variable. Thus, the change doesn't apply. If your vendor somehow backported the YACC variable commit and somehow magically requires newer bison than a 4.19 kernel. You SHOULD revert the commit to force it to use host BISON instead. We don't break majority for the minority. And as all kernels are going to be >4.19 eventually, it doesn't make sense to burden majority of cases with a variable.

It is not a supported case by Lineage so that's your problem. You should also define bison pkg data of your bison if you consciously override bison of build system.

> 
> It's far from the majority of cases yet... and given the lengths we go to for legacy support - I doubt it will be for the next 8 years or more.

This is not a legacy v. new problem. Given the information we have, it is highly likely that the issue was introduced by the OP. 

As:
1. 4.14 doesn't have LEX or YACC variable so unless related change is backported, nothing will apply. 
2. Standard 4.14 kernels doesn't require bison at all. If OP's kernel does require bison for some reasons, with PATH isolation, it is not possible to build BEFORE "add bison and flex". OP must have a prebuilt bison in kernel tree or have overridden bison here with bison of their choice or whitelisted the HOST bison. 
3. If OP does whitelist/override (which is unsupported), a corresponding bison pkg data directory must be specified for their bison, which OP SHOULD do when they choose to override/whitelist.

None of these cases is supported.
